f(t)|) |g(y)| ≤ 1`, then perhaps we can use `sup_t |f(t)| > 0` to get `|g(y)| ≤ 1 / (sup_t |f(t)|)`? But we don't yet have `(sup_t |f(t)|) |g(y)| ≤ 1`.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps a direct approach is better: Suppose for contradiction that there exists some `y` such that `|g(y)| > 1`. Then for any `t`, we have `|f(t)| < 1 / |g(y)| < 1` (from `|f(t)| |g(y)| ≤ 1`). Thus, `|f(t)| < 1` for all `t`. Now, find `t` such that `f(t) ≠ 0` (exists since `f` is not identically zero). Plug `x = t`, `y = y` in the original equation:\n`f(t + y) + f(t - y) = 2 f(t) g(y)`.\nBut `|f(t + y) + f(t - y)| ≤ 2`, and `2 |f(t)| |g(y)| > 2 |f(t)|`. Not sure yet.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps it's better to revisit the first approach where we use that the supremum is not zero:\nLet `M = sup |f(t)|`. Then `M > 0` (since `f` is not identically zero) and `M ≤ 1`.\nFrom `f(t + y) + f(t - y) = 2 f(t) g(y)`, we get:\n`2M ≥ |f(t + y) + f(t - y)| = 2 |f(t)| |g(y)|`.\nThus, for any `t`, `|f(t)| |g(y)| ≤ M`.\nBut since for any `ε > 0` there exists `t` with `M - ε < |f(t)| ≤ M`, taking `ε → 0`, we get that `M |g(y)| ≤ M`, so `|g(y)| ≤ 1`.\nBut we need to formalize that step. Take `t_n` with `|f(t_n)| → M`. Then for each `n`, `|f(t_n)| |g(y)| ≤ M`, so in the limit `M |g(y)| ≤ M`.\n\n**Formal Proof Sketch:**\n1. Define `M = sup_{t ∈ ℝ} |f(t)|`. Then `0 < M ≤ 1`.\n2. For any fixed `y` and any `x`, we have `2 |f(x)| |g(y)| ≤ 2M`, because `|f(x + y) + f(x - y)| ≤ 2M = 2 |f(x)| |g(y)|`.\n   - Actually, it's better: `2 |f(x)| |g(y)| = |f(x + y) + f(x - y)| ≤ |f(x + y)| + |f(x - y)| ≤ 2M`.\n   - So `|f(x)| |g(y)| ≤ M` for any `x` and any `y`.\n3. Since `M = sup |f(x)|`, there exists a sequence `x_n` such that `|f(x_n)| → M`.\n   - Taking `x = x_n` in the inequality gives `|f(x_n)| |g(y)| ≤ M`.\n   - Taking `n → ∞` gives `M |g(y)| ≤ M`, hence `|g(y)| ≤ 1`.\n\nBut perhaps we don't need sequences: since for all `x`, `|f(x)| ≤ M`, then `|f(x)| |g(y)| ≤ M`, but we also have points where `|f(x)|` is arbitrarily close to `M